commit.message:
Significant rewrite.

The main reason for this rewrite, and major change in user experience
is to do the tests in subtests. Now one call to match() counts as one
test (with one exception, see below), while still doing lots of (sub)tests.

Other changes:
  -  All non-public subroutines have been made lexical. This implies that
     Perl 5.26 is now required.
  -  Subroutines now use signatures.
  -  We no longer turn on the utf8 layer on STDOUT, nor do we check
     ${^UNICODE} anymore to determine how to escape certain characters.
     Instead, we check whether the utf8 layer is set on STDOUT.
  -  The "comment" argument to match is now a full alias for "name", and
     is considered obsolete.
  -  Whether we expect captures is not determined whether pattern or
     keep_pattern is given, but it's based on the capture parameter.
  -  We now discourage the use of keep_pattern. We still support it for
     compatability reasons. If given, we run match() twice (and it will
     count as two tests), once with the pattern argument, and not expecting
     captures, and once with pattern set to the given keep_pattern, and
     the captures set.
  -  We eliminated the no_keep_message option.
  -  "test" and "reason" messages, as well as file names and line numbers
     are now displayed as diagnostic messages instead of stuffing all the
     information in a single test comment.
  -  We eliminated the use of $&, and we're using ${^MATCH} instead.
    (In combination with /p).
  -  We use @{^CAPTURE} to capture the positional variables, instead of
     $$_ for 1 .. $#-.
Added a "use lib '.'" to prepare for 5.26

Allow specifying how non printable ASCII characters are displayed.

We offer the following options:

  0  No escaping what so ever. Not recommended, as newlines will confuse
     prove.
  1  Only escape newline, linefeed, and tab, showing as \n, \r and \t.
  2  Show any character which is not a printable ASCII character as
     a hex escape. This is the default, unless -CO is in effect.
  3  Show any character which is not a printable ASCII character as
     a named escape, using the Unicode name (\N{UNICODE NAME})
  4  Display the non-printable ASCII as hex escapes, and leave all other
     characters "as is". This is the default when -CO is in effect
     (${^UNICODE} is true).

In the cases 2, 3, 4, newlines, linefeeds and tabs are displayed as in 1.

Fix my() inside my().

Which seems to be a regression in 5.23.*. Older perl just did the right thing.

Eliminate the use of given.

given() is nowadays marked as experimental, and hence, will warn if used.
Remove outcommented code and fix up some comments.
Use the pattern instead of name/comment if they are empty.
Test permissions of the files (Author tests)
Skip tests on failures with Changes.
Require that version in README matches the package version.

Remove ghost_* parameters.

This was introduced to test certain aspects of Regexp::Common510.
However, it turns out we actually do not need this.

Also, renamed some variables into something more sensible.
